// Nested loops where the inner body has a branch that jumps to the outer header — exercises
// the labeled `continue 'outer_label` form. With OtherLoop collapsed to Latch and iterative
// resolution at outer-loop time, node 5's jump to 1 (outer header) becomes `continue 'loop_1`,
// emitted *inside* the inner loop body. The inner label is needed because an unlabeled
// `continue` would target the inner loop.
//
//         0
//         |
//      ┌─→1───→6 (exit when outer cond false)
//      │  │
//      │ ┌2←┐
//      │ │  │
//      │ ┌3─┘ (inner back-edge: 3 → 2)
//      │ │
//      └─┘ (4's jump: 4 → 1, an OtherLoop edge from inner body to outer header)
//
// Inner header = 2, inner latch = 3 (back-edge 3 → 2), inner body = {2, 3}.
// Outer header = 1, outer latch = 4 (back-edge 4 → 1).
// The structuring sees 4 → 1 inside inner's natural exit path; after the inner loop is
// emitted, outer's insert_breaks reclassifies that raw Jump as continue 'loop_1.

code,0,1
cond,1,2,6
cond,2,3,4
code,3,2
code,4,1
code,6
